<TEXT>
prime minister mieczyslaw rakowski says 
his new government is less broadly based than he wanted because 
four opposition members refused to join his cabinet 
in my opinion opposition entry into the goverment would have 
changed quite strongly the political situation in poland and 
created a new situation favorable to the idea of national 
reconciliation rakowski said 
rakowski spoke at his first news conference as prime minister 
friday just after the sejm or parliament voted 3631 to approve a 
cabinet made up mostly of members of the ruling polish united 
workers party the communist party 
when asked what role the outlawed trade union solidarity was 
playing rakowski said i dont limit democratization to the 
recognition of solidarity i dont think that the restoration of 
solidarity may be proof of the fact that our country is becoming 
more democratic 
but a catholic deputy said in a parliament speech friday that 
authorities must regard solidarity the first independent union in 
the soviet bloc as a permanent fixture of the political scene 
there is no doubt that union pluralism is today a basic but 
one of the many problems to be solved from the wide package of 
reform which awaits us zygmunt kostarczyk said 
rakowski had left open four cabinet positions for what he called 
members of the constructive opposition but said opposition 
figures refused to join his government 
rakowski said he offered cabinet posts to catholic church 
adviser witold trzeciakowski independent economist julian 
auleytner catholic intellectual andrzej micewski and journalist 
alexander paszynski 
when he was named prime minister sept 27 rakowski said he 
hoped to broaden the communistdominated government and gain 
popular support 
the cabinet which rakowski nominated thursday includes a new 
generation of young party members to oversee economic affairs but 
senior party members retained the key interior defense and foreign 
ministries in all parliament approved nine new ministers 
one of rakowskis chief tasks as prime minister will be to 
revive the failing economy inflation stands at 60 percent 
consumer goods from cheese to winter coats are in short supply and 
workers continue to press for wage increases 
rakowski declined to say exactly when the roundtable talks with 
solidarity and he seemed cautious about the results 
i am against getting excited about the round table he said 
we will see how the first round will go what kinds of positions 
or views will appear 
solidarity was crushed with the imposition of martial law in 
1981 
solidarity leader lech walesa agreed to end a wave of strikes in 
august after the government agreed to roundtable talks on the 
future of solidarity 
in a related development about fifty miners dismissed from 
their jobs after the strikes demonstrated outside the communist 
party headquarters in warsaw friday eyewitnesses said 
they held up banners saying we dont want to overthrow the 
round table we demand only to have our jobs back 
solidarity has said it will discuss dismissals and repression of 
former strikers at the roundtable talks 
rakowski replaced zbigniew messner whose cabinet resigned sept 
19 after criticism for mishandling the partyapproved economic 
reform program it was the first time the entire government stepped 
down in postwar poland 
</TEXT>
