hundreds of northwest airlines passengers 
have been stricken with an illness that may be linked to 
contaminated food served on several flights a malady so 
distressing that some victims said they thought they were going 
to die 
we have cases all over the country said michael osterholm 
the state epidemiologist the minnesota health department received 
hundreds of calls thursday and friday he said 
five of the reports which came to light after members of the 
minnesota vikings football team were sickened were confirmed as 
cases of the bacterial illness shigellosis an intestinal infection 
that causes severe diarrhea gripping abdominal pain and other 
symptoms that can last for five to seven days 
the one common phrase being reported to investigators is 
people thinking they have never been so sick that they thought 
they were going to die osterholm said 
he said he expects additional cases to be confirmed in the next 
few weeks 
it would not surprise me if there eventually were hundreds of 
confirmed cases but right now any number estimate would be 
premature he said 
those who were confirmed with the illness took northwest flights 
that originated in minneapolisst paul and went to nashville 
tenn detroit seattle and newark nj osterholm said the 
malady was reported among members of the minnesota vikings after 
they took a charter flight to miami 
the flights occurred between sept 25 and oct 4 osterholm said 
illnesses that could be shigellosis were reported by people who 
were on about 30 flights the latest of which was oct 8 
we have no reason to believe it is happening now he said 
the confirmed illnesses have been traced to food prepared in 
marriott corps airline kitchen at the minneapolisst paul 
international airport the facility prepares 100000 meals a week 
for northwest 
the outbreak came to light after 21 players and staff of the 
vikings became acutely ill two to five days after their game in 
miami oct 2 osterholm said thursday that after the game the 
vikings some of their family members and two miami locker room 
workers ate marriott sandwiches that were brought from minneapolis 
in addition to contracting the disease from contaminated food 
the illness spreads easily from person to person 
two members of the vikings brad edwards and tim irwin were 
hospitalized after eating the sandwiches the st paul pioneer 
press dispatch reported irwin a 280pound tackle lost 9 pounds 
there were no other reports of hospitalizations in the united 
states 
