george bush riding the momentum of last 
weeks debate will focus on proven themes and big states as he 
tries to hold or expand his lead in the final three weeks of the 
presidential campaign aides say 
they say he will not stray far from the themes he has already 
honed on the campaign trail crime the death penalty prison 
furloughs in massachusetts a strong military and will break 
little if any new ground on issues 
although bush is enjoying a widening lead in public opinion 
polls over democratic presidential nominee michael dukakis he and 
his top campaign officials are insisting they will not permit 
themselves to become complacent 
thats the last thing i want to have happen bush said at 
weeks end as it became clear his campaign was enjoying a 
postdebate surge 
while maintaining a busy schedule bush can be expected to run a 
cautious playitsafe campaign in the days ahead 
that means sticking to his basic campaign stump speech speaking 
mostly before friendly audiences having few news conferences and 
seldom departing from a wellrehearsed script 
bush himself told reporters i dont feel any pressure to put 
out a lot of new programs at this stage in the campaign weve 
got a lot of programs out there 
he conceded that youll see a lot of similarity in his 
campaign speeches in the next three weeks with the triedandtested 
