<TEXT>
the huge accommodation module of the 
oil rig that exploded and burned in july was hauled saturday from 
the north sea to be searched for 112 bodies still missing from the 
worlds worst oilfield disaster 
when the piper alpha oil rig exploded in flames on july 6 167 
workers perished and most of the bodies were not recovered 
it is believed many may be in the accommodation unit where 
workers had their living quarters 
in silence and gathering fog the 1000ton steel structure the 
size of a fourstory building emerged from the sea hoisted by 
cranes water pouring from drainage holes drilled in its sides by 
divers 
there were no cheers from the 400 offshore oilfield workers who 
took part in the operation 120 miles from scotlands northeastern 
coast 
a spokesman for occidental petroleum corp the piper alpha 
owner said the module would be secured to a giant barge for 
transport to calm waters in the orkney islands the journey is 
expected to take two days once there 40 police officers will 
search for bodies 
police said relatives would be spared the distress of 
identifying the bodies and the remains will be flown to aberdeen 
for identification 
the module had been upsidedown almost 500 feet below the 
surface of the sea 
the module big enough to contain a movie theater and gymnasium 
was to be welded to a barge for its final journey to the flotta 
terminal 130 miles away in the orkneys said occidental spokesman 
alex blakemilton 
a smaller accommodation module from the oil rig platform was 
lifted from the seabed tuesday but no bodies were found inside 
john brading occidentals chief executive for britain said 
the successful completion of this complex lifting operation will 
i am sure bring great relief to the relatives of the missing men 
as well as to the offshore crews who have been directly involved 
with the task 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

