the sunday telegraph reported that a soviet double 
agent who worked for british intelligence for 10 years said that in 
1983 the soviets were convinced the west was about to attack 
it based its report on excerpts from the book the storm 
birds by gordon brookeshepherd which deals with soviet 
defectors 
the sunday telegraph account said that in an interview soviet 
defector oleg gordievski told brookeshepherd that president reagan 
toned down his evil empire approach to the kremlin after 
gordievski warned about mounting tension in the soviet leadership 
the newspaper said gordievski was the top official of the soviet 
kgb secret police in britain when he defected in july 1985 
it said gordievski passed on warnings about the level of war 
panic in the soviet union and that led to a change of western 
tactics 
gordievski was quoted in the storm birds as saying the 
soviets believed an attack from the west would use military 
maneuvers as camouflage and a november 1983 nato exercise codenamed 
able archer triggered the panic 
he also was quoted as saying the kremlin sent an urgent order to 
all kgb agents abroad to report anything that might indicate the 
west was preparing to launch a nuclear strike 
in britain this involved looking for signs of food stockpiling 
emergency blood banks and noting whether prime minister margaret 
thatcher was driving more often than usual to buckingham palace 
according to the account 
referring to reagan the book said the white house had until 
then gordievskis warning fondly believed that through the 
reports to moscow of men like anatoly dobrynin soviet ambassador 
to washington over more than two decades the picture of an 
essentially peaceloving and peaceseeking america would have been 
presented 
it now transpired that for much of the time even this 
respected veteran had been telling his masters more or less what 
they wanted to hear 
in an article accompanying the excerpt brookeshepherd wrote 
that gordievski said it was the sovietled invasion of 
czechoslovakia in 1968 to crush a liberalcommunist government that 
led to gordievskis defection after a prolonged spiritual and 
emotional struggle 
the newspaper said gordievski had been recruited in copenhagen 
in 1974 by british intelligence 
