<TEXT>
the agriculture department is going to buy an 
additional 120 million worth of food for distribution to needy 
people next year under recently enacted antihunger legislation 
assistant secretary john w bode said friday the food will be 
purchased by usda and sent to food banks and other outlets 
beginning in january and continuing through september 1989 
bode said the quantities of food purchased will depend on 
market conditions at the time but that plans now call for the 
commodities to include peanut butter canned pork beans egg mix 
and raisins 
the program is the temporary emergency food assistance program 
or tefap which began in december 1981 when president reagan 
authorized distribution of governmentowned food to help reduce the 
surplus stockpile of certain commodities notably cheese but also 
including a variety of other products 
as tefap developed the surpluses dwindled so that the 
department has had to trim the list of items for donation after 
giving away more than 5 billion pounds of food worth more than 5 
billion 
that is when congress stepped in with the recent hunger 
prevention act of 1988 which authorizes about 165 billion over 
three years to bolster the governments emergency food programs 
including more funds for food stamps school breakfasts childcare 
and summer food programs 
the law also extended tefap for two years and provided money for 
the additional purchases 
bode said that in addition to the 120 million of additional 
purchases the usdas commodity credit corp still has 1219 
million worth of food available for tefap and is continuing to make 
it available at current monthly rates of 6 million pounds of 
butter 4 million pounds of cornmeal and 12 million pounds of flour 
thus the total tefap funding is 2419 million for the remainder 
of the fiscal year that began on oct 1 said dianne durant a 
spokeswoman for the departments food and nutrition service 
in addition she said congress earmarked 40 million to help 
feed homeless people at soup kitchens and shelters foods most 
likely to be provided are canned pork dry beans and canned fruit 
vegetables and juices 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

