<DOCNO> AP881015-0164 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the little tax bill that nobody loved is 
hanging by a thread because house and senate negotiators cant 
agree on how big it should be 
house negotiators are insisting on a bill that raises at least 
45 billion over three years to pay for 45 billion of selected 
tax cuts senators backed by the reagan administration are 
refusing to budge above 3 billion 
the dispute torpedoed closeddoor discussions on the bill friday 
and house aides were saying the measure probably is dead sen max 
baucus dmont who is heading the senate delegation was not so 
pessimistic 
we have not selected the pallbearers yet he said adding 
that senate aides would look over the latest house proposal over 
the weekend then well see what the mood is next week the 
final week of the 100th congress baucus said 
tax bills usually are highly popular items with members of 
congress simply because lawmakers have found there is little that 
makes voters happier than a tax cut 
but because of a monumental budget deficit there is no surplus 
money in the treasury to finance a lot of tax cuts so every dollar 
of tax cut for peter must be offset by a dollar tax increase on 
paul 
that is why this years bills are so relatively small about 
75 billion as originally passed by the house and just under 3 
billion in the senate version 
the bills two years in the making have not been a toppriority 
item for either the house the senate or the reagan administration 
the only big push for passage has come from accountants eager to 
have some errors and ambiguities in the 1986 tax law cleared up 
and from farmers demanding relief from the tax on diesel fuel 
either bill would respond to those concerns both bills also 
extend several expiring tax benefits provide targeted relief to 
lowerincome homebuyers workers attending night school farmers 
and others and raise other taxes to pay for the benefits the 
senate package also includes a bill of rights to help taxpayers 
involved in disputes with the internal revenue service 
the exchange of offers before negotiations were broken off 
indicated some form of the bill of rights will be in the final bill 
if there is one in addition it would repeal the requirement 
that farmers pay the diesel tax on offroad fuel and then apply for 
a refund and also prevent mutual fund owners from paying tax on 
phantom income from those funds 
the negotiations are complicated by the fact that sen lloyd 
bentsen dtexas chairman of the senate finance committee is also 
his partys candidate for vice president ever since he was 
nominated in july there have been indications he did not want to 
be identified closely with a bill that opponents could point to as 
new evidence of a democratic tendency to raise taxes to finance 
more spending 
senator bentsens position all year long has been that he is 
not interested in raising a lot of taxes to be plowed back into 
other tax cuts said bill maddox a finance committee spokesman 
on the other hand rep dan rostenkowski dill head of the 
house delegation points out that his bill passed the house by a 
38025 vote the widest margin for a tax bill in 20 years his 
aides say it is difficult for rostenkowski to drop provisions that 
got such broad support 
the senate bill passed by an even more lopsided margin 871 
in backing away from their 7 billionplus package house 
negotiators agreed to drop a moneyraiser opposed by the reagan 
administration that would require corporations to pay more tax on 
dividends from stocks they own in other companies 
the house also agreed to modify slightly its call for repeal of 
the completedcontract accounting method used by defense 
contractors and many large builders this method allows 
postponement on some building profits 
under the proposed compromise the benefit would be retained 
only for construction of housing 
