<TEXT>
telephone callers using bell credit cards will 
have a wider range of services available to them under a federal 
judges order requiring the regional bell companies to stop 
discriminating in favor of atampt on longdistance calls 
the ruling gives the bell companies 75 days to begin routing 
longdistance calls that are not dialed directly to the 
longdistance carrier to which the caller has presubscribed such 
as mci or sprint 
calls placed with a bell calling card or which use a bell 
operator now go over atampt lines automatically unless the caller 
has a credit card with another company and uses an access code to 
bypass the local bell operator and reach that longdistance carrier 
thus the ruling applies primarily to nonatampt longdistance 
customers who for whatever reason do not carry a nonatampt credit 
card it also will allow holders of such cards to charge local 
calls which now can be done only with a bell card 
us district judge harold h greene ordered the bell companies 
to cease discriminating in favor of atampt with respect to their 
calling cards and pay phones by jan 1 1989 the fifth 
anniversary of the court order that stripped atampt of its local 
operating companies 
five years is long enough for the baby bells as they are 
called to provide equal access to their local networks for all 
longdistance companies and the court expects the parties to 
meet its deadline greene said 
callers using credit cards issued by mci communications corp 
us sprint communications co and other atampt competitors are not 
afforded the same services as atampt and bell card holders for 
example they are unable to charge local calls to their card or to 
charge longdistance calls made through a bell operator 
before divestiture when american telephone amp telegraph co and 
the local companies were part of the giant bell system they used 
the same database to validate and bill creditcard calls 
after divestiture because of the use of the common database 
atampt and the bell companies issued the same calling card number for 
any particular customer 
consequently all longdistance calls made with bell cards were 
directed to atampt also calls from bellowned pay phones also were 
routed to atampt 
mci the nations secondlargest longdistance company after 
atampt complained about the arrangement to the justice department 
which asked greene to stop the bells from discriminating in favor 
of atampt 
in his decision greene ordered the bells by jan 1 to make 
available to all longdistance carriers the same validation data 
for its calling cards that the company provides to atampt on the 
same prices terms and conditions as are extended to atampt this 
means bell cardholders will be able to charge longdistance calls 
to their carrier of choice 
he also ruled that the owners of premises where bell pay phones 
are located will be able to choose by jan 1 which longdistance 
company the calls from that phone will be routed to 
nearly half of all calls from bell pay phones are 
operatorassisted yielding more than 1 billion in revenues a year 
most of it to atampt greene said 
in addition greene said the baby bells must inform its 
callingcard customers that longdistance calls charged to the card 
will be provided by a longdistance company not the bell company 
but not always the carrier to which they presubscribed as a 
dial1 service on their home phone 
the judge also said the regional companies could keep in 
circulation but only for atampt customers bell credit cards that 
carry the same international number as used by atampt provided they 
issue cards to other customers listing the international number of 
the longdistance company to which they presubscribed 
 
</TEXT>
